						<summary>

						<p>North wall of the first <hi rend="italic">prākāra</hi> of the Pālvaṇṇanāthasvāmi temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Perumāḷ Parākramapāṇḍya Śaka 1469, Regnal year 4:</hi></p>						

						<p>This incomplete record furnishes the details of date <hi rend="italic">viz.,</hi> Śaka 1469, regnal year 4, Plavaṅga, Vaikāśi ba 3, Monday, <hi rend="italic">Śubha-yōga, Ṟishabha-karaṇa</hi> and Aśvati-nakshatra.</p>						

						<p>It seems to record a gift as <hi rend="italic">kāṇi-āṭchi</hi> by Māṇikkaṉ to Perum-Villavarāyaṉ Tiru[viḻalam] Kāṅgīyaṉ of Irāśēndiram.</p>						

						<p>The record further mentions the various titles of a king whose name is not given. The epithets like <hi rend="italic">Bhuvanēkavīra, Chandrakulapradīpa, Jayanthamaṅgala-puravarādhīśvara,</hi> etc., are found attributed to king Aḻagaṉ Perumāḷ Parākramapāṇḍya, the father of Chaḍaiyavarmaṉ Tribhuvanachakravarti Kōnērinmaikoṇḍāṉ Tirunelvēli[perumāḷ*], who was born in the nakshatra Aśvati (Aśvini) in a record of the same date. Hence, the king who bears similar epithets in the record under review may be identified with Aḻagaṉ Perumāḷ Parākrama-pāṇḍya. (See <hi rend="italic">A.R.Ep.,</hi> 1908, No. 277). </p>						

						</summary>
